<section id="about"><h2>About Mental Health</h2><p>Mental health includes our emotional, psychological, and social well-being. It affects how we think, feel, and act. College life can be extremely stressful, it's absolutely okay to seek help and take care of your mind.</p></section>
<section id="home" class="visible"><h2>Welcome to MindEase ðŸŒ¿</h2><p>Your very own safe space for mental haealth awareness and the necessary support.</p></section>
<section id="quiz" class="quiz"><h2>Self-Assessment Quiz</h2><form id="quizForm"><p>1. Do you feel stressed or anxious often?<br><input type="radio" name="q1" value="2" required> Often <input type="radio" name="q1" value="1"> Sometimes <input type="radio" name="q1" value="0"> Rarely</p><p>2. Are you sleeping well?<br><input type="radio" name="q2" value="0" required> Yes <input type="radio" name="q2" value="1"> Sometimes <input type="radio" name="q2" value="2"> No</p><p>3. Are you able to eat properly?<br><input type="radio" name="q3" value="0" required> Yes <input type="radio" name="q3" value="1"> Sometimes <input type="radio" name="q3" value="2"> No</p><p>4. Do you find it hard to focus on studies?<br><input type="radio" name="q4" value="2" required>Often <input type="radio" name="q4" value="1"> Sometimes <input type="radio" name="q4" value="0"> Rarely</p><p>5. How often do you feel isolated or lonely?<br><input type="radio" name="q5" value="2" required>Often <input type="radio" name="q5" value="1"> Sometimes <input type="radio" name="q5" value="0"> Rarely</p><button type="button" onclick="calculateScore()">Submit</button></form><div class="result" id="result"></div></section>
<section id="tips"><h2>Coping Tips</h2><ul><li>Take short breaks during study sessions.</li><li>Practice deep breathing or meditation for 5 minutes daily.</li><li>Talk to a friend, mentor, or counsellor about how you feel.</li><li>Maintain a balanced diet and regular sleep schedule.</li><li>Write a short journal entry each night to clear your mind.</li></ul></section>
<section id="myths"><h2>Common Myths About Mental Health</h2><ul><li><strong>Myth:</strong> Mental health problems are rare.<br><strong>Fact:</strong> 1 in 4 people experience mental health challenges in their lifetime.</li><li><strong>Myth:</strong> Only weak people struggle with mental health issues.<br><strong>Fact:</strong> Mental health struggles can affect anyone, regardless of strength or character.</li><li><strong>Myth:</strong> Talking about mental health makes it worse.<br><strong>Fact:</strong> Open conversations help reduce stigma and encourage support.</li><li><strong>Myth:</strong> Therapy is only for people with serious problems.<br><strong>Fact:</strong> Therapy is helpful for anyone seeking self-improvement or emotional balance.</li><li><strong>Myth:</strong> Students don't need to worry about mental health.<br><strong>Fact:</strong> Academic pressure, social expectations, and transitions can impact student well-being.</li><li><strong>Myth:</strong> If a person has a mental health condition, it means the person has low intelligence.<br><strong>Fact:</strong> Mental illness, like physical illness, can affect anyone regardless of intelligence, social class, or income level.</li><li><strong>Myth:</strong> Poor mental health is not a big issue for teenagers. They just have mood swings caused by hormonal fluctuations and act out due to a desire for attention.<br><strong>Fact:</strong> Fourteen per cent of the world's adolescents experience mental-health problems. Globally, among those aged 10â€“15, suicide is the fifth most prevalent cause of death, and for adolescents aged 15â€“19 it is the fourth most common cause.</li></ul></section>
